'''Yuki Shrine''' (由岐神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} located in {{ill|Sakyō-ku|ja|左京区|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Kyoto|ja|京都市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Also referred to as '''Yuki Myōjin''' (靫明神), it enshrines {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大己貴命|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Sukunabikona|ja|少彦名命|1=Sukunabikona|qq=draft|qq=draft}} as its main deities, collectively called "Yuki Daimyōjin." The shrine serves as the {{ill|chinjusha|ja|鎮守社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} of {{ill|Kurama-dera|ja|鞍馬寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

== History ==
Originally, the enshrined deities were worshipped within the imperial palace. Following a series of disasters, including a major earthquake in {{ill|Heian-kyō|ja|平安京|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and the {{ill|Tengyō Rebellion|ja|天慶の乱|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Emperor Suzaku ordered the relocation of the shrine to {{ill|Mount Kurama|ja|鞍馬山|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|940|ja|940th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Tenkei 3). It was established as the chinju shrine of Kurama-dera to protect the northern border of the capital. The {{ill|Kurama Fire Festival|ja|鞍馬の火祭|qq=draft|qq=draft}} originates from the villagers' torchlight procession to welcome the shrine's deities during this relocation.

The name "Yuki Myōjin" derives from the practice of offering {{ill|quiver|ja|靫|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (yuki) to the shrine during times of national crisis, praying for peace and stability. According to {{ill|Tsurezuregusa|ja|徒然草|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, this tradition was similar to practices at {{ill|Gojō Tenjin Shrine|ja|五條天神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, which enshrines the same deities.

The worship hall and main hall were rebuilt in {{ill|1607|ja|1607th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Keichō 12) under the patronage of Toyotomi Hideyori.

== Enshrined Deities ==
* Main deities: {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大己貴命|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Sukunabikona|ja|少彦名命|1=Sukunabikona|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
* Auxiliary deities: Eight additional kami

== Grounds ==
* Main Hall - Renovated in 2023.
* Sanpōkōjin Shrine - Dedicated to {{ill|Kōjin|ja|三宝荒神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, revered as a deity of fire and hearth protection.
* Shrine Office
* Shironaga Benzaiten Shrine - Dedicated to {{ill|Benzaiten|ja|弁財天|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
* Kanja Shrine - Dedicated to {{ill|Susanoo|ja|素戔嗚命|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a deity of prosperity.
* Iwakami Shrine - Dedicated to {{ill|Kotoshironushi|ja|事代主命|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Ōyamatsumi|ja|大山祇命|1=Ōyamatsumi|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
* Ōsugi Shrine - Features sacred trees, including three cedar trees and one {{ill|Machilus|ja|カゴノキ|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
* {{ill|Hachiman Shrine|ja|八幡宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
* Worship Hall (割拝殿) - Designated as an {{ill|Important Cultural Property (Japan)|ja|重要文化財|1=Important Cultural Property (Japan)|2=ja|3=重要文化財|lt=Important Cultural Property|qq= (Japan)|4=ko|5=일본의_중요문화재|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in the Momoyama architectural style, rebuilt in Keichō 12 (1607).

== Cultural Properties ==
=== Important Cultural Properties ===
* Worship Hall (割拝殿)
* Pair of stone komainu - Deposited at the {{ill|Kyoto National Museum|ja|京都国立博物館|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, displayed as "stone lions"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yukijinjya.jp/about/index.html|title=About Yuki Shrine|publisher=Yuki Shrine|accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kyohaku.go.jp/jp/theme/floor1_5/f1_5_koremade/shishi_2016.html|title=Special Exhibit: Lions and Komainu|publisher=Kyoto National Museum|accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref>.

=== Kyoto City Natural Monuments ===
* Sacred trees of Ōsugi Shrine (three cedar trees and one machilus)

=== Kyoto City Intangible Folk Cultural Properties ===
* {{ill|Kurama Fire Festival|ja|鞍馬火祭|qq=draft|qq=draft}}

== Additional Information ==
* Entry to the shrine grounds is free. However, since it is within the precincts of Kurama-dera, visitors must pay the temple's admission fee of 500 yen for high school students and older (free for younger children and discounts for Eizan Railway one-day pass holders). Early morning and evening access is free.
* Visitors using the [[:en:Kurama-dera_Cable|Kurama-dera Cable]] pass by Yuki Shrine. To visit after worshiping at the Kurama-dera Main Hall, visitors must walk back down the approach.

