'''Yuki Shrine''' (由岐神社) is a [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shinto shrine]] located in [[:en:Sakyō-ku, Kyoto|Sakyō-ku]], [[:en:Kyoto|Kyoto]]. Also referred to as '''Yuki Myōjin''' (靫明神), it enshrines {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大己貴命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōkuninushi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 大国主}} and {{ill|Sukunabikona|ja|少彦名命|1=Sukunabikona|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sukunabikona|13=User:Immanuelle/Sukunabikona|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to スクナビコナ}} as its main deities, collectively called "Yuki Daimyōjin." The shrine serves as the [[:en:Chinjusha|chinjusha]] of [[:en:Kurama-dera|Kurama-dera]].
== History == Originally, the enshrined deities were worshipped within the imperial palace. Following a series of disasters, including a major earthquake in [[:en:Heian-kyō|Heian-kyō]] and the {{ill|Tengyō Rebellion|ja|天慶の乱|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tengyō Rebellion|qq=}}, Emperor Suzaku ordered the relocation of the shrine to [[:en:Mount Kurama|Mount Kurama]] in [[:en:940|940]] (Tenkei 3). It was established as the chinju shrine of Kurama-dera to protect the northern border of the capital. The {{ill|Kurama Fire Festival|ja|鞍馬の火祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kurama Fire Festival|qq=}} originates from the villagers' torchlight procession to welcome the shrine's deities during this relocation.
The name "Yuki Myōjin" derives from the practice of offering {{ill|quiver|ja|靫|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/quiver|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 箙}} (yuki) to the shrine during times of national crisis, praying for peace and stability. According to [[:en:Tsurezuregusa|Tsurezuregusa]], this tradition was similar to practices at {{ill|Gojō Tenjin Shrine|ja|五條天神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gojō Tenjin Shrine|qq=}}, which enshrines the same deities.
The worship hall and main hall were rebuilt in [[:en:1607|1607]] (Keichō 12) under the patronage of Toyotomi Hideyori.
== Enshrined Deities == * Main deities: {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大己貴命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōkuninushi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 大国主}}, {{ill|Sukunabikona|ja|少彦名命|1=Sukunabikona|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sukunabikona|13=User:Immanuelle/Sukunabikona|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to スクナビコナ}} * Auxiliary deities: Eight additional kami
== Grounds == * Main Hall - Renovated in 2023. * Sanpōkōjin Shrine - Dedicated to {{ill|Kōjin|ja|三宝荒神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōjin|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}, revered as a deity of fire and hearth protection. * Shrine Office * Shironaga Benzaiten Shrine - Dedicated to {{ill|Benzaiten|ja|弁財天|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Benzaiten|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 弁才天}}. * Kanja Shrine - Dedicated to {{ill|Susanoo|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|素戔嗚命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo-no-Mikoto|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to スサノオ}}, a deity of prosperity. * Iwakami Shrine - Dedicated to {{ill|Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto|lt=Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto|lt=Kotoshironushi|ja|事代主命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kotoshironushi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 事代主}} and {{ill|Ōyamatsumi|ja|大山祇命|1=Ōyamatsumi|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyamatsumi|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyamatsumi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to オオヤマツミ}}. * Ōsugi Shrine - Features sacred trees, including three cedar trees and one {{ill|Machilus|ja|カゴノキ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Machilus|qq=}}. * [[:en:Hachiman shrine|Hachiman Shrine]] * Worship Hall (割拝殿) - Designated as an [[:en:Important Cultural Property (Japan)|Important Cultural Property]] in the Momoyama architectural style, rebuilt in Keichō 12 (1607).
== Cultural Properties == === Important Cultural Properties === * Worship Hall (割拝殿) * Pair of stone komainu - Deposited at the [[:en:Kyoto National Museum|Kyoto National Museum]], displayed as "stone lions"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yukijinjya.jp/about/index.html|title=About Yuki Shrine|publisher=Yuki Shrine|accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kyohaku.go.jp/jp/theme/floor1_5/f1_5_koremade/shishi_2016.html|title=Special Exhibit: Lions and Komainu|publisher=Kyoto National Museum|accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref>.
=== Kyoto City Natural Monuments === * Sacred trees of Ōsugi Shrine (three cedar trees and one machilus)
=== Kyoto City Intangible Folk Cultural Properties === * {{ill|Kurama Fire Festival|ja|鞍馬火祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kurama Fire Festival|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 鞍馬の火祭}}
== Additional Information == * Entry to the shrine grounds is free. However, since it is within the precincts of Kurama-dera, visitors must pay the temple's admission fee of 500 yen for high school students and older (free for younger children and discounts for Eizan Railway one-day pass holders). Early morning and evening access is free. * Visitors using the [[:en:Kurama-dera_Cable|Kurama-dera Cable]] pass by Yuki Shrine. To visit after worshiping at the Kurama-dera Main Hall, visitors must walk back down the approach.
